<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: CAMARILLO; GIFTS SURPRISE FATHER REUNITED WITH KIDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After driving 1,764 miles in two days with the two children he had been 
searching for since August, James Moats returned home to Camarillo just in time 
for Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
 Moats said he and his children, James, 5, and Jessica, 9, were taken by 
surprise by the Christmas decorations and presents left inside the house by 
friends and relatives. 
</P>
<P>
 "We drove up and saw all the decorations and figured that was it. Then we went 
inside and we were just like -- whoa! We were real surprised," Moats said. 
</P>
<P>
 The family was reunited Thursday, when Moats found the children living with 
their mother in Missouri. Sherry Kay Moats, 35, was arrested on child abduction 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
 Saturday, the children were riding bicycles and playing outside their house in 
Camarillo. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're just having a great time. They're happy to be home," Moats said. 
</P>
<P>
 He said his mother, friends and Deputy Dist. Atty. Pam Grossman, who helped 
find the children, were among his Christmas visitors. 
</P>
<P>
 Moats said that while he was pleased with his family reunion, his holiday joy 
was tempered because of his knowledge of other parents searching for children 
who are still missing. 
</P>
<P>
 "Unfortunately, there's a lot of other kids out there who aren't as lucky," he 
said. IRA E. STOLL 
</P>
</TEXT>
