<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY IN BANKRUPTCY; OFFICIALS SEEK TO REACT BUT NOT SCARE THE PUBLIC; 
CRISIS: MANY CITY AND SCHOOL DISTRICT LEADERS ADOPT A WAIT-AND-SEE ATTITUDE. 
BUT A FEW INSIST ON TOUGH TALK AND CALL FOR IMMEDIATE STUDY OF POTENTIAL CUTS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRA; DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE, ; RUSS LOAR, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As they respond to an unfolding financial crisis, city and school district 
leaders say they face a dilemma: how to deal swiftly and soberly with the 
situation without unduly alarming the public before all the facts are in. 
</P>
<P>
 It's a balancing act leaders said they must perform at public meetings, in 
their offices as they field phone calls from residents, and even at the 
supermarket as neighbors approach them. 
</P>
<P>
 Many officials have adopted a conservative wait-and-see attitude, wary of 
frightening residents even when the financial picture appears grim. 
</P>
<P>
 At a Santa Ana school board meeting in which officials announced that the bond 
debacle might mean larger classes, trustee Audrey Yamagata-Noji warned against 
publicizing a "hit list" of potential cutbacks until the district's losses are 
clear. "People freak out and I don't blame them," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 But other officials insist that the financial crisis must be met with tough 
talk and austere planning, even though its full effects probably won't be known 
for months. 
</P>
<P>
 In Irvine, school board member Hank Adler last week suggested that officials 
immediately draw up a list of deep cutbacks, declaring that "the time for 
denial is over." Another board member then accused Adler of needlessly 
frightening residents and employees. 
</P>
<P>
 "Hank's approach is where you draw out the worst case scenario in very large 
terms," board member Mike Regele said. "The scenario I want to follow is a 
little more conservative and incremental. Certainly we need to be thinking 
about worst-case scenarios, but we need to be careful of that." 
</P>
<P>
 Officials' efforts to address to the crisis in any decisive way have been 
complicated by its fluid nature. With high-level meetings occurring throughout 
the day and night, they said, it is often difficult to speak with certainty 
about what's going on. 
</P>
<P>
 Not surprisingly, concern about the collapsed pool is more intense in cities 
with large investments than those with smaller ones. 
</P>
<P>
 Irvine, with $209 million in the pool, has held several emergency council 
meetings over the past month. The city has gone from twice monthly meetings to 
weekly meetings. In Cypress, with only about $5 million in the pool, the crisis 
has not emerged as a major issue. 
</P>
<P>
 The county announced two weeks ago that the fund has lost roughly 27% of its 
value over the past year. But many local officials refuse to concede that their 
agencies will suffer any long-term losses, insisting instead that they are due 
back every penny of their investments. 
</P>
<P>
 So far, cities and school districts have responded to the crisis by delaying 
capital projects, imposing hiring freezes and clamping down on spending. But 
most officials interviewed fear the worst is yet to come. 
</P>
<P>
 "We still don't have the full story. That makes it difficult," said Paula 
Werner, Irvine's mayor pro tem. "For now, I don't want to allude to cuts. . . . 
Instead of throwing up a trial balloon, I want to know all the facts." 
</P>
<P>
 Officials said they are being cautious in part to spare city and school 
employees any needless panic, especially around the holidays. Many employees 
already have experienced several rounds of belt-tightenings and layoffs as 
agencies adjusted to the statewide economic downturn. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've gone though this recession. Restructuring government has changed 
people's lives," Werner said. "Staff morale is low. People are nervous to begin 
with." 
</P>
<P>
 In many cities and school districts, leaders said they've tried to avoid 
squabbling in an effort to approach the crisis with a united front. 
</P>
<P>
 But elsewhere, differences in the way elected officials approach to the 
situation are showing. 
</P>
<P>
 Cathy Ann Brooks, a newly elected trustee for the Placentia-Yorba Linda 
Unified School District, proposed last week that an independent committee of 
residents be formed to advise the board on bond matters. 
</P>
<P>
 "Unless you believe in the tooth fairy, there is going to come a time when 
there will be cuts," Brooks said. 
</P>
<P>
 But others on the board expressed doubts about her proposal, saying they don't 
need advice from a committee and aren't even sure cuts will be necessary. 
"There may not be any problems down the road," trustee Jerry Brakebill said. 
"We don't know what we may have to cut, if anything at all." 
</P>
<P>
 The district has more than $53 million in the pool. 
</P>
<P>
 A similar debate is going on in the Irvine Unified School District, with $102 
million frozen in the fund, the most of any Orange County school system. 
</P>
<P>
 Adler, a newly elected board member, said it is time for the district to act. 
He urged the district to prepare for a $30-million loss and called on school 
board members to eliminate their $400-a-month stipends. 
</P>
<P>
 "In this situation, my philosophy is: Prepare for the worst and hope for the 
best," said Adler, an accountant. "People have told me, don't sugarcoat it, we 
want to know everything." 
</P>
<P>
 But a veteran board member said Alder is moving too fast. 
</P>
<P>
 "If we really did have, as Mr. Adler suggested, a $30-million problem, we are 
bankrupt," Regele said. "It's not possible to cut $30 million out of a 
$100-million budget. But I don't believe that is the magnitude of the problem." 
</P>
<P>
 Adler's comment could also send the wrong message about how the board is 
responding to the crisis, Regele said. "The implication was made that we were 
not embracing the magnitude of the problem and we are not moving. That simply 
is not true," he said. "We need to be moving quickly to assess the extent of 
the damage. But we also need to get a realistic assessment of it." 
</P>
<P>
 Times correspondent Jon Nalick contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Full Run; Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
