<P>
THE BOWLS / DAILY REPORT; HOLIDAY; GAME CAME NATURALLY TO BIAKABATUKA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 His name is Tshimanga Biakabatuka, but his North American friends call him 
Tim. 
</P>
<P>
 Michigan's sophomore running back, who plays behind Tyrone Wheatley, has taken 
an unusual route to major college football.Biakabatuka was born in Zaire and as 
a child moved with his family to Montreal. He should have played soccer. Or ice 
hockey. 
</P>
<P>
 "I never chose football," Biakabatuka said as Michigan prepared for its game 
Friday against Colorado State at San Diego Jack Murphy Stadium. "Football came 
to me and I fell in love with it." 
</P>
<P>
 That was six years ago during a physical education class in high school. A 
coach, looking for an extra body for his team, called upon the African 
immigrant. It did not take Biakabatuka long to excel. 
</P>
<P>
 "Football is a sport easy to learn," he said. "After three years I was pretty 
comfortable with the rules." 
</P>
<P>
 Now Biakabatuka is one of three finalists for Quebec's 1994 athlete of the 
year after a strong season filling in for the oft-injured Wheatley. ELLIOTT 
ALMOND 
</P>
